{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496735"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1410"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1410"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.12,0.05,0.13,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53901"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1410"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39363"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"201"},{"type":"tags","id":"1200"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10711"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16217"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33889"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37228"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53901"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old man presents to his oncologist for a follow-up appointment during treatment for a non-seminomatous germ cell tumour. He complains of insidious and progressive breathlessness on exertion. He has no other significant medical history. He is a non-smoker and currently does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly short of breath. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 125/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals bilateral basal inspiratory crackles. High-resolution CT of the chest shows interspersed areas with a ground-glass appearance in both lung bases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bleomycin toxicity","Lymphangitis carcinomatosa","Goodpasture syndrome","Sarcoidosis","Acute hypersensitivity pneumonitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ebleomycin toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E. Bleomycin is a chemotherapeutic agent commonly used in the treatment of germ cell tumours, typically in combination with etoposide and cisplatin. Pulmonary toxicity is a well-documented and use-limiting adverse effect of bleomycin, with life-threatening interstitial lung disease occurring in up to 10% of patients. The insidious onset of dyspnoea, bilateral basal crackles, and ground-glass opacities on CT are characteristic findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key step in managing bleomycin-induced lung injury is immediate and permanent discontinuation of bleomycin. Risk factors for this complication include age \u0026gt;40 years, renal insufficiency, concurrent chemotherapy or radiation therapy, and cigarette smoking. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphangitis carcinomatosa \u003C/strong\u003Erefers to the malignant infiltration and inflammation of the pulmonary interstitial lymphatics secondary to the metastatic spread of malignancy from a primary site with the absence of tumour cells in pulmonary arteries and/or capillaries. The clinical picture of a patient with lymphangitis carcinomatosa usually comprises of chest pain and unexplained dyspnoea on a background of metastatic disease. On exam, the patient may have low-grade fever, tachypnoea, and tachycardia. On CT, nodular interlobular septa \u0026amp; peribronchovascular interstitium thickening is considered relatively specific for lymphangitis carcninomatosa, although ground glass opacity may be seen as well due to interstitial oedema or parenchymal invasion of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGoodpasture syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as anti-GBM disease, is an autoimmune condition that typically affects both the lungs and kidneys. It usually presents with haemoptysis and signs of acute kidney injury, neither of which are present in this case. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is another cause of interstitial lung disease that can affect young adults. However, the CT findings in sarcoidosis typically include nodules and thoracic lymphadenopathy, which are not described here. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute hypersensitivity pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a mixed type-III and type-IV hypersensitivity reaction to inhaled antigens.  Patients usually present with fever, malaise, cough, and dyspnea that often resolves quickly after cessation of antigen exposure. Prolonged exposure can progress to pulmonary fibrosis. On exam, you would hear inspiratory crackles or inspiratory squeaks, while HRCT shows ground glass opacity with the relatively sparing of the lung bases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary toxicity is a well-documented and use-limiting adverse effect of bleomycin, a chemotherapy agent commonly used for germ cell tumours, with life-threatening interstitial disease occurring in up to 10% of patients.","Immediate and permanent discontinuation of bleomycin is the key step in managing bleomycin-induced lung injury."],"references":["Mikolasch TA, Garthwaite HS, Porter JC. Update in diagnosis and management of interstitial lung disease. Clin Med 2017;17:146-53. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6297625/","Krishna R, Chapman K, Ullah S. Idiopathic Pulmonary Fibrosis. [Updated 2023 Jul 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448162/","AK AK, Mantri SN. Lymphangitic Carcinomatosis. [Updated 2023 Jul 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560921/","Chandra D, Cherian SV. Hypersensitivity Pneumonitis. [Updated 2023 Jul 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499918/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39363"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1410"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39363"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-27T15:55:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-27T15:56:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1410"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53901"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"d